“The delay has been occasioned by late submission of data necessary for the compilation as a result of COVID-19 related challenges,” said Collins Omondi, Director General of The Kenya National Bureau of Statistics, in a statement. Earlier on Wednesday, central bank Governor, Patrick Njoroge told reporters the economy was likely to grow 3.1% this year, reflecting growing optimism in the East African nation as it navigates its way through the coronavirus crisis. --Reuters--